[3] Sub-Saharan Africa: Spillover events
- 24 Feb 2021
Forbes (abridged, edited)
https://apple.news/AqaOTkhBpSdyxuM1VZS_OqA


I reported recently on the 2 new outbreaks of Ebola in Sub-Saharan Africa. At the time, there were 4 cases in the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC) and 8 cases in Guinea. Since then, another 2 or 3 cases have been found in the DRC.

This is the 12th Ebola epidemic in the DRC, and the 2nd in Guinea.

Ebola is a zoonotic pathogen, meaning that the virus is maintained in a wild animal species, or reservoir. Under conditions that aren't particularly well understood, it periodically spills over from animal populations into people. Ebola 1st came to global attention in 2015 during the West Africa epidemic that spread widely throughout Guinea, Liberia, and Sierra Leone, and less extensively in Italy, Mali, Nigeria, Senegal, Spain, the UK, and the USA.

A map published in the scientific journal PLoS Neglected Tropical Diseases in 2015 [see comment below] shows where Ebola virus outbreaks have historically occurred along with the animal species implicated in the spillover process. The timeline on the right shows when these outbreaks occurred, including an outbreak of an unidentified pathogen in DRC in 1972 that is now suspected to have been Ebola.

It has been 5 years since that map was published. Since then, there have been 5 more outbreaks, bringing the total to 27, including (1) a 2018 outbreak in Equateur province (DRC); (2) an epidemic that lasted from August 2018 to June 2020 in the Eastern region of Kivu (DRC), which also spread to Uganda; (3) an outbreak last year [2020], again in Equateur province (DRC); and (4) and (5) the new outbreaks in the DRC and Guinea.

This invites us to ask the question: is the spillover of Ebola increasing in frequency?

If we look back at just the last 10 years, there have been 9 outbreaks of Ebola since 2010 -- almost one per year -- compared with just 18 in the preceding 38 years, or roughly one every other year.

From this point of view, it certainly looks like Ebola outbreaks have been increasing in frequency. But another look at the timeline shows a curiosity. Ebola seems to have been in a lull with no reported human cases between 1980 and 1993. (There were, however, a few outbreaks in non-human primates in the early 1990s). Viewed this way, one might think of Ebola as having 3 epochs:

1972-1979: 5 outbreaks in 8 years
1980-1993: 0 outbreaks in 14 years
1994-present: 22 outbreaks in 28 years.

The average time between outbreaks in each of these epochs is shown in the following figure [see URL].

From this perspective, the frequency of outbreaks now is not meaningfully different than it was in the 1970s, when Ebola was described. So, which historical view is correct? Either way, we have a mystery to solve.

If we take the timeline view, considering each outbreak, it seems that, indeed, Ebola spillover events are increasing in frequency. Why? What is happening to cause the increase in outbreaks? One hypothesis concerns environmental change, as Ebola outbreaks seem to correlate with shifts in vegetation and the transition between dry and wet seasons. Another explanation concerns the frequency of encounters between humans and wild animals, perhaps because of land conversion or increased demand for animal protein from hunting.

However, if we take the epochal view, grouping outbreaks into distinct periods, then there would seem to be no evidence for an increase.

However, there is the mystery of the lull in the 1980s and early 1990s. Why would there not have been any outbreaks for 14 years when they occurred every one to 2 years on either side of this period? Did we simply miss them for some reason or were there really that many fewer outbreaks?

In either case, it is reasonable to expect that Ebola will continue to spill over into human populations. Identifying spillover risk factors, developing surveillance systems for early detection, and securing healthcare and public health resources for rapid response are needed to protect against future Ebola epidemics. Fortunately, the benefits of these investments also have a kind of "spillover," providing protection not only from Ebola but other endemic and emerging diseases too.

--
Communicated by:
Mary Marshall
<mjm2020@googlemail.com>

[Alexander KA, Sanderson CE, Marathe M, et al. What Factors Might Have Led to the Emergence of Ebola in West Africa? PLoS NTD Published: 4 Jun 2015 https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pntd.0003652.

Abstract:
"An Ebola outbreak of unprecedented scope emerged in West Africa in December 2013 and presently continues unabated in the countries of Guinea, Sierra Leone, and Liberia. Ebola is not new to Africa, and outbreaks have been confirmed as far back as 1976. The current West African Ebola outbreak is the largest ever recorded and differs dramatically from prior outbreaks in its duration, number of people affected, and geographic extent. The emergence of this deadly disease in West Africa invites many questions, foremost among these: why now, and why in West Africa? Here, we review the sociological, ecological, and environmental drivers that might have influenced the emergence of Ebola in this region of Africa and its spread throughout the region. Containment of the West African Ebola outbreak is the most pressing, immediate need. A comprehensive assessment of the drivers of Ebola emergence and sustained human-to-human transmission is also needed in order to prepare other countries for importation or emergence of this disease. Such assessment includes identification of country-level protocols and interagency policies for outbreak detection and rapid response, increased understanding of cultural and traditional risk factors within and between nations, delivery of culturally embedded public health education, and regional coordination and collaboration, particularly with governments and health ministries throughout Africa. Public health education is also urgently needed in countries outside of Africa in order to ensure that risk is properly understood and public concerns do not escalate unnecessarily. To prevent future outbreaks, coordinated, multiscale, early warning systems should be developed that make full use of these integrated assessments, partner with local communities in high-risk areas, and provide clearly defined response recommendations specific to the needs of each community."

Certainly, lessons have been learned from and since the 2013 West African outbreak. In addition, vaccines are now available as are effective antivirals. Treatment of patients is greatly improved. But equally important are communication and education, which must be maintained as well as public health infrastructure. Resources should be committed to maintaining clinics, which can be used for other endemic diseases once an outbreak ends. Training of staff should continue.

With these practices, should Ebola re-emerge, the community will be well prepared to respond immediately. - Mod.LK]
